			"entries": [
				"You touch an object that isn't already affected by this spell and program a single action into it.  When a certain trigger occurs, the object magically springs to life, executing the programmed action and then ending the spell. ",
				"The executed action must be one that is directly related to how the target object is used, and takes no more than one action to perform. It will typically be the {@action Utilize|XPHB} action for mundane objects or the {@action Magic|XPHB} action for magic items, but other actions may be possible, at the DM's discretion. The object can move, but no further than 5 feet as part of executing the action. The action cannot involve making an {@variantrule attack roll|XPHB}, and if it requires an {@variantrule ability check|XPHB}, roll it using your appropriate ability score. ",
				"You specify the trigger when you finish casting the spell. The action executes immediately after the trigger occurs, regardless of whether you want it to. ",
				"For example you could program a potion to administer itself to the creature carrying it when that creature drops to 0 {@variantrule Hit Points|XPHB}. ",
				"You can optionally cause the material component to be consumed by the spell. If you do, the spell's duration becomes 'until dispelled', and it doesn't end when the programmed action is executed. The action can't be triggered again for 6 seconds. The spell ends early if the object is ever more than 10 feet from where it was when you cast the spell."
			],
			"source": "CoopersCompendiumofComplexities",
			"components": {
